article.description:
Lindsay Whalen matched her career-high with 21 points and the Connecticut Sun beat the Washington Mystics 80-70 Monday night to even the best-of-three WNBA Eastern
Conference semifinal.
article.headline: Sales sets playoff record with seven steals

images.name: Whalen Lindsay 040927 195x262
images.caption: Rookie Lindsay Whalen paced the Sun with 21, including 15-of-16 from the free throw line.

article.linkText: Sun turn up heat, force deciding game
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Lindsay Whalen didn't miss much Monday night. Perfect from the field and almost perfect from the free throw line, the rookie guard matched her career-high with 21 points to lead the Connecticut Sun to an 80-70 win over the Washington Mystics. The victory evened their best-of-three WNBA Eastern Conference semifinal.
Rookie Lindsay Whalen paced the Sun with 21, including 15-of-16 from the free throw line.
The deciding third game will be Wednesday night at Connecticut. "It's just me getting in the lane and wanting to create things if I'm not going to get my own shot," she said. "You just have to be aggressive and that's the only way I know how to play." Whalen set a team record making 15 of 16 free throws, while the Sun were 30-of-32 from the line, the third best mark in league playoff history. Whalen's 15 free throws were a team record and the second most in WNBA playoff history. She was 3-for-3 from the field. Nykesha Sales added 13 points for the Sun and set a WNBA playoff record with a career-best seven steals. Connecticut scored 21 points on 17 Washington turnovers. "We just imposed our will on the game and it all started on the defensive end," Whalen said. The Mystics came in on a roll, having won six of their last seven games including an eight-point win over the Sun on Saturday. Much of their success has come without star Chamique Holdsclaw, who left the team for undisclosed medical issues. Rookie Alana Beard figured prominently in the turnaround, but on Monday Connecticut's defense neutralized her for much of the game. Beard finished with 15 points, scoring six in the final 2 minutes when the Sun had the game in hand. She also had three blocked shots. Connecticut's Wendy Palmer-Daniel, who shared the WNBA's Most Improved Player of the Year award Monday with Indiana's Kelly Miller, added 12 points. Tamicha Jackson led the Mystics with 17 points, including three 3-pointers. The Sun hit seven of their first nine shots in under 5 minutes to take a 19-3 lead. All five starters scored in that spurt, then pressured Washington into six turnovers in the early minutes. "It was the first five minutes, they set the tone," Beard said. "They attacked the basket. We allowed them to do what they wanted to." Sales played solid defense for the Sun in the first half, finishing with five rebounds, all on the defensive end, and five steals. "We were determined to get the win," Sales said. "The energy and focus were there." The Washington bench helped the Mystics chip away and get within six points with under 7 minutes to play. Jackson had 10 points, including two 3-pointers, in the half. Reserve forward Asjha Jones scored eight of her 10 first-half points in the closing minutes and the Sun took a 42-34 lead. "We went up and down the court with the same pace the other night in Washington, but the ball didn't go in the basket," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. The Sun led by as many as 20 points midway through the second half. Debbie Black hit her first 3-pointer of the season as the shot clock expired to give the Sun a 63-43 lead with 11:48 remaining. The Mystics cut the deficit to nine on a 3 by Stacey Dales-Schuman with 2:26 left, but the Sun made 11 of 12 free throws to seal the win. "We got tentative out there and we didn't match their intensity to start the game," Mystics coach Michael Adams said.
